messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full request path:
- /api/users/{id}

All HTTP methods acceptable:
- false

Method-level acceptability (based on the source code):
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- In server.js the user routes are mounted with app.use('/api/users', userRoutes), so every route in routes/userRoutes.js is prefixed with /api/users.
- In routes/userRoutes.js the path router.route('/:id') registers handlers for .delete(...), .get(...), and .put(...). That makes the full path /api/users/:id â€” expressed with a path parameter as /api/users/{id}.
- There is no router.all or wildcard that would allow every method; therefore "all methods" is false.
- Only GET, PUT and DELETE are explicitly registered on this path in the code, so those are marked true.
- HEAD, POST, OPTIONS, TRACE, PATCH are not explicitly registered for /:id in the router code, so they are marked false. (Although some frameworks/servers may auto-handle HEAD for GET, the instruction required basing acceptability only on the code, not on runtime/behavioral assumptions.)
- Note: the registered methods are protected by middleware (protect, admin) in the routes, but that affects authorization, not whether the method is defined.
